Problem #1

By graphing the data this way I am able to see that the sepal width data rises to a certain point and then decreases steadily after that with local peaks, but ultimately decreasing.

For sepal length, the data increases and decreases often. Multiple local peaks and lows.

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

ggplot(data = iris) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes (x = Sepal.Length))

ggplot(data = iris) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes (x = Sepal.Width))

Comments:

  • A bar plot is not really appropriate here; that would be useful for discrete (rather than continuous) data. You are looking for a histogram, with some work on picking a reasonable bin width. For example, see below.
  • Also be sure your final graphs have appropriate labels.
ggplot(iris) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = Sepal.Length), binwidth = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Alternate: Sepal Length Distribution", x = "Sepal Width", y = NULL)

Problem #2

By adding the categorical variable species, I am able to take a closer look at each species of flower such as the sepal length and width in one graph.

ggplot(data = iris) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = Sepal.Length, fill = Species), binwidth = 1) +
  labs(title = "Species", 
       x = "Sepal Length",
       y = "Sepal Width")

Comments:

  • Your binwidth is a little large here; this gives you only five categories.
  • Your y-axis is not width. (You have not produced a graph for the distribution of widths here.)
  • The color does help differentiate, but these are still hard to read plotted on top of each other. It will help to separate the graphs by species with a facet_wrap, like below: 
ggplot(data = iris) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = Sepal.Length, fill = Species), binwidth = .45) +
  facet_wrap( ~ Species) +
  labs(title = "Alternate: Sepal Length by Species", 
       x = "Sepal Length",
       y = "Count")
